```c
char *getLine(FILE *f) {
    char *buffer = NULL;
    size_t buffer_size = 0;
    ssize_t bytes_read;

    while (1) {
        bytes_read = getline(&buffer, &buffer_size, f);
        if (bytes_read == -1) {
            if (feof(f)) {
                return buffer;
            } else {
                printf("[X] Error reading file\n");
                return NULL;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This function uses the `getline` function to read a line from the file. The `getline` function reads a line from the file and stores it in the `buffer` string, which is dynamically allocated to accommodate the line. The `buffer_size` variable keeps track of the current size of the `buffer` string.

The function continues to read lines until it reaches the end of the file. When it reaches the end of the file, it returns the `buffer` string. If there's an error reading the file, it prints an error message and returns `NULL`.

